mt_raw:
The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has set the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(a) To preserve capital;
(b) To ensure that the entire monetary base is fully supported at all times by highly liquid U.S. dollar-denominated assets;
(c) To ensure sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) To seek investment returns as much as possible within the framework of the above (a) to (c), in order to safeguard the fund's long-term purchasing power.

With respect to the valuation of financial assets and liabilities measured at fair value, the audit procedures included:
- Understanding the valuation processes for different categories of financial assets and liabilities, including related control measures;
- Evaluating and testing the control measures, including application controls over computer systems;
- Obtaining external confirmations regarding the valuation, existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and liabilities;
- Verifying prices from independent sources if market quotations were used;
- If valuation techniques with parameters based on observable market data were employed, evaluating whether the valuation methods were appropriate and whether the assumptions were reasonable, and verifying the parameters from independent sources; and
- If valuation techniques with parameters not based on observable market data were employed, evaluating whether the valuation methods were appropriate, and whether the assumptions and parameters were reasonable.

With respect to the Future Fund deposits, the audit procedures included:
- Assessing whether the accounting policies used to measure these deposits and the interest earned are appropriate;
- Reviewing the methodology for calculating the annual rate of return linked to the long-term growth portfolio;
- Verifying the calculation of the fixed rate determined based on the past performance of the reference investment portfolio, the annual rate of return linked to the long-term growth portfolio, and the composite rate determined based on these two rates;
- Verifying the amount of interest accrued calculated using the composite rate; and
- Reviewing the presentation and disclosure of these deposits and the interest earned in the financial statements.

During the audit, I will apply professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism. I will also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement in the financial statements due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures to address these risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to support my opinion. Because fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omission, false representation, or override of internal controls, the risk of not detecting material misstatements arising from fraud is higher than the risk of not detecting material misstatements arising from errors;
- Understand the internal control relevant to the audit
